Classifying images with convolutional neural networks¶

Introduction¶

The CIFAR-10 dataset contains 60,000 RGB images 32 pixels square. There are in 6000 examples of each of the ten objects and animals, with no overlap. The AlexNet architecture was built in TensorFlow as a baseline model, and then was modified using ResNet style residual connections and a dropout layer. To reduce overfitting a series of image transformations were used to change the size, color, and orientation of the training set.

Results¶

  • Conventional machine learning techniques struggle with image data. In order to converge on a logistic regression model the data had to be compressed from 3,072 features to 400 with greyscale and resizing operations. Even restricting the data to a single binary classification problem resulted in accuracy barely better than a coin flip (59.67%).
  • A sequential convolutional neural network was able to vastly improve on this, with the addition of residual connections, a dropout layer, and data augmentation pushing the accuracy to almost 80% in the 10 category problem.

  • Tuning the type, amount, and rate of data augmentation to provide enough new information without degrading the images beyond recognition was a challenging task, but paid off in better model performance. The use of iterative training sprints kept the model from getting stuck in unproductive paths without leaking too much information from the validation set. The use of dilation also kept the model from over fitting the data, but made it so hard to learn that the model never exceeded the baseline model performance.

Data¶

  • the CIFAR-10 dataset is available withing the Keras module

Full code¶

In this notebook we train three neural networks to identify images from the CIFAR-10 dataset. We explore how changes in architecture like residual connections and dropout layers can improve performance and lighten the number of model parameters. We also explore the use of dilation and data augmentation to generalize the model, making use of an iterative training environment to steer the model towards peak performance on validation and test data.

# Function to plot confusion matrix from class
def plot_confusion_matrix(cm, class_names):
    """
    Returns a matplotlib figure containing the plotted confusion matrix.
    
    Args:
       cm (array, shape = [n, n]): a confusion matrix of integer classes
       class_names (array, shape = [n]): String names of the integer classes
    """
    
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(8, 8))
    plt.imshow(cm, interpolation='nearest', cmap=plt.cm.Blues)
    plt.title("Confusion matrix")
    plt.colorbar()
    tick_marks = np.arange(len(class_names))
    plt.xticks(tick_marks, class_names, rotation=45)
    plt.yticks(tick_marks, class_names)
    
    # Normalize the confusion matrix.
    cm = np.around(cm.astype('float') / cm.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis], decimals=2)
    
    # Use white text if squares are dark; otherwise black.
    threshold = cm.max() / 2.
    
    for i, j in itertools.product(range(cm.shape[0]), range(cm.shape[1])):
        color = "white" if cm[i, j] > threshold else "black"
        plt.text(j, i, cm[i, j], horizontalalignment="center", color=color)
        
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.ylabel('True label')
    plt.xlabel('Predicted label')
    return figure

# function to print model accuracies from class
def model_accuracy(model, x_train, train_labels, x_valid, validation_labels, x_test, test_labels):
    train_prob = model.predict(x_train)
    train_pred = np.argmax(train_prob, axis=1)
    train_acc = accuracy_score(train_pred, train_labels.squeeze())
    print('Train Accuracy: {:.4f}'.format(train_acc))

    validation_prob = model.predict(x_valid)
    validation_pred = np.argmax(validation_prob, axis=1)
    validation_acc = accuracy_score(validation_pred, validation_labels.squeeze())
    print('Validation Accuracy: {:.4f}'.format(validation_acc))

    test_prob = model.predict(x_test)
    test_pred = np.argmax(test_prob, axis=1)
    test_acc = accuracy_score(test_pred, test_labels.squeeze())
    print('Test Accuracy: {:.4f}'.format(test_acc))
    
    # Confusion matrix for test set
    conf_mat_data = confusion_matrix(test_pred, test_labels)
    conf_df = pd.DataFrame(conf_mat_data, columns=class_names, index=class_names)
    display(conf_df)
    
    return conf_df

def make_grey_20_20(img):
    '''Convert 32x32x3 rgb image to 20x20 greyscale'''
    # convert image to PIL format
    pil_img = Image.fromarray(img)

    # resize using PIL anti-aliasing
    pil_img = pil_img.resize((20, 20), Image.ANTIALIAS)

    # convert back to numpy
    img2 = np.array(pil_img.getdata()).reshape(20, 20, 3)
    img2 = np.where(img2 < 0, 0, img2)
    img2 = np.where(img2 > 255, 255, img2)

    # convert to greyscale from 
    # stackoverflow.com/questions/41971663/
    img3 = np.dot(img2[...,:3], [0.299, 0.587, 0.114])

    return img3

def its_a_bird_its_a_plane(X, y):
    '''Select images of birds and planes, reduce to 20x20 greyscale and flatten.'''
    # count planes (0) and birds (2) in target labels
    size_plane = np.sum(y == 0)
    size_bird = np.sum(y == 2)
    
    # initialize matrices of just bird and plane with zeroes
    X_plane = np.zeros((size_plane, 20, 20))
    X_bird = np.zeros((size_bird, 20, 20))
    
    # initialize target with plane = 0, bird = 1
    y_plane = np.zeros(size_plane, dtype = 'int')
    y_bird = np.ones(size_bird, dtype = 'int')
    
    # initialize counters 
    count_bird = 0
    count_plane = 0
    
    # loop over images
    for i in range(len(y)):
        # if a plane (0), convert 32x32x3 image to 20x20 greyscale and add to X_plane
        if y[i] == 0:
            X_plane[count_plane] = make_grey_20_20(X[i])
            count_plane += 1
        
        # if a bird (2), convert 32x32x3 image to 20x20 greyscale and add to X_bird
        elif y[i] == 2:
            X_bird[count_bird] = make_grey_20_20(X[i])
            count_bird += 1
    
    # merge the bird and plane images and target labels
    X_bird_plane = np.concatenate((X_bird, X_plane), axis=0)
    y_bird_plane = np.concatenate((y_bird, y_plane), axis=0)
    
    # flatten 20x20 images to 400 feature array
    X_bird_plane_flat = X_bird_plane.reshape(X_bird_plane.shape[0], 400)
    
    return (X_bird_plane_flat, y_bird_plane)

Get accuracy baseline with logistic regression¶
In [4]:
# convert 10x32x32x3 problem to a 2x400 one: pick two targets (bird and plane)
# extract all images matching these targets, resize to 20x20, convert to greyscale
# and flatten to a 400 feature numpy array
start = time()
X_bp_train, y_bp_train = its_a_bird_its_a_plane(train_images, train_labels)
X_bp_valid, y_bp_valid = its_a_bird_its_a_plane(validation_images, validation_labels)

# train a logistic regression model on birds vs planes
solve_start = time()
logit = LogisticRegression(max_iter = 5000, solver = 'sag', n_jobs = -2)
logit.fit(X_bp_train, y_bp_train)

# predict on training and validation data
y_hat_train = logit.predict(X_bp_train)
y_hat_valid = logit.predict(X_bp_valid)

# get accuracy scores
acc_train = accuracy_score(y_bp_train, y_hat_train)
acc_test = accuracy_score(y_bp_valid, y_hat_valid)

print('Table 1')
print(f'Conversion took {solve_start - start:.2f} seconds. Solving took {time() - solve_start:.2f} seconds.')
print("Training data accuracy is {:2.2f}%".format(acc_train * 100))
print("Validation data accuracy is {:2.2f}%".format(acc_test * 100))

  • Table 1: Five hours on a Colab GPU core was unable to converge a solution using the full number of image features. To simplify the problem, the classification was reduced to a binary classification between birds and planes, image size was reduced from 32x32 to 20x20, and the RGB layers were converted to a single greyscale layer. The resulting model converged in 32 seconds, but was only able to achieve a 59.67% accuracy rate on the calidation data, barely above chance (50%).

Baseline sequential neural network: Alexnet¶
In [6]:
def alexnet_model():
    model = Sequential(name="alexnet_model")

    # Layer 1: 3x3 convolution w/ stride 1, & 48 features.
    model.add(Conv2D(48,
                  kernel_size=(3,3),
                  strides=(1,1),
                  activation='relu',
                  padding='same', 
                  input_shape=(32, 32, 3)))
    # Followed by Max Pooling
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2))) # 16x16

    #Layer 2: 3x3 convolution w/ stride 1, & 96 features.
    model.add(Conv2D(96,
                  kernel_size=(3,3),
                  activation='relu',
                  padding='same'))
    # Followed by Max Pooling
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2))) # 8x8


    #Layer 3: 3x3 convolution w/ stride 1, & 192 features.
    model.add(Conv2D(192,
                  kernel_size=(3,3),
                  activation='relu',
                  padding='same') )
    # Followed by Max Pooling
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2))) # 4x4

    #Layer 4: 3x3 convolution w/ stride 1, & 192 features.
    model.add(Conv2D(192,
                  kernel_size=(3,3),
                  activation='relu',
                  padding='same'))
    # Followed by Max Pooling
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2))) # 2x2

    #Layer 5: 3x3 convolution w/ stride 1, & 256 features.
    model.add(Conv2D(256,
                  kernel_size=(3,3),
                  activation='relu',
                  padding='same'))
    # Followed by Max Pooling
    model.add(MaxPool2D(pool_size=(2,2),strides=(2,2))) # 1x1

    # Flatten
    model.add(Flatten()) # flat

    #Layer 6: Dense layer to 512 neurons.
    model.add(Dense(512, activation='tanh'))

    #Layer 7 : Dense layer to 256 neurons.
    model.add(Dense(256, activation='tanh'))

    #Prediction: Dense layer to 10 neurons.
    model.add(Dense(10, activation='softmax'))

    return(model)

In [7]:
def alex_resnet_model():
    # input, block 1
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=(32, 32, 3), name="img")
    x = layers.Conv2D(48, kernel_size=(3,3), strides=(1,1), padding="same", activation="relu")(inputs)
    block_1_pool2 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2))(x) # 16x16

    # block 2
    x = layers.Conv2D(96, kernel_size=(3,3), strides=(1,1), padding="same", activation="relu")(block_1_pool2)
    block_2_merge = layers.Concatenate(axis = 3)([x, block_1_pool2]) 
    block_2_pool2 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2))(block_2_merge) # 8x8

    # block 3
    x = layers.Conv2D(144, kernel_size=(3,3), activation="relu", padding="same")(block_2_pool2)
    block_3_merge = layers.Concatenate(axis = 3)([x, block_2_pool2])
    block_3_pool2 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2))(block_3_merge) # 4x4

    # block 4
    x = layers.Conv2D(240, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu")(block_3_pool2)
    block_4_merge = layers.Concatenate(axis = 3)([x, block_3_pool2])

    # flatten and extract features
    block_4_global= layers.GlobalMaxPool2D()(block_4_merge) # flat
    x = layers.Dense(256, activation='tanh')(block_4_global) 
    x = layers.Dropout(0.1)(x)
    x = layers.Dense(64, activation='tanh')(x) 
    outputs = layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')(x)

    alex_resnet = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name="alex_resnet")
    return alex_resnet

def alex_resnet_dilation():
    # input, block 1 and 2 combined
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=(32, 32, 3), name="img")
    d1 = layers.Conv2D(48, kernel_size=(3,3), strides=(1,1), dilation_rate=2, activation="relu")(inputs) #28x28
    d2 = layers.Conv2D(96, kernel_size=(3,3), strides=(1,1), padding="same", activation="relu")(d1)
    d3 = layers.Conv2D(96, kernel_size=(3,3), strides=(1,1), dilation_rate=2, activation="relu")(d2) #24x24
    d4 = layers.Conv2D(96, kernel_size=(3,3), strides=(1,1), padding="same", activation="relu")(d3)
    d5 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(3,3), strides=(3,3))(d4) #8x8

    # block 3
    x = layers.Conv2D(144, kernel_size=(3,3), activation="relu", padding="same")(d5)
    block_3_merge = layers.Concatenate(axis = 3)([x, d5])
    block_3_pool2 = layers.MaxPooling2D(pool_size=(2,2), strides=(2,2))(block_3_merge) # 4x4

    # block 4
    x = layers.Conv2D(240, kernel_size=(3,3), padding="same", activation="relu")(block_3_pool2)
    block_4_merge = layers.Concatenate(axis = 3)([x, block_3_pool2])

    # flatten and extract features
    block_4_global= layers.GlobalMaxPool2D()(block_4_merge) # flat
    x = layers.Dense(256, activation='tanh')(block_4_global) 
    x = layers.Dropout(0.1)(x)
    x = layers.Dense(64, activation='tanh')(x) 
    outputs = layers.Dense(10, activation='softmax')(x)

    alex_resnet_dilation = keras.Model(inputs, outputs, name="alex_resnet_dilation")

    return alex_resnet_dilation

# Random Rotation function, modified from class
def rand_rotation_im(img, count):
    rand_angle = np.random.choice(list(range(1, 5 * (count + 1))) + list(range(360 - 5 * (count + 1), 359)))
    img = ndimage.rotate(img, rand_angle, cval=img.min(), reshape=False)
    img = ndimage.rotate(img, rand_angle, cval=img.min(), reshape=False)
    img = np.where(img < 0, 0, img)
    img = np.where(img > 1, 1, img)
    return img

def show_transform(func):
    fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 10, figsize = (16,20));
    axes[0].imshow(x_train[0]);
    axes[0].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
    axes[0].get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    axes[0].set(title = 'Original')
    for i in range(1,10):
        axes[i].imshow(func(x_train[0], i*2));
        axes[i].set_title(f'Round {i*2}')
        axes[i].get_xaxis().set_visible(False)
        axes[i].get_yaxis().set_visible(False)
    pass

print('Figure 4: Image rotations with increasing range in deeper rounds' )

Exaggerate image edges¶
In [10]:
# Emphasize image edges
def image_edges(img, count):
    # convert numpy to PIL
    img2 = img * 255
    img2 = img2.astype('uint8')
    pil_img = Image.fromarray(img2)

    # edge enhance, return to numpy
    pil_img = pil_img.filter(ImageFilter.EDGE_ENHANCE_MORE)
    img3 = np.array(pil_img.getdata()).reshape(pil_img.size[1], pil_img.size[0], 3)
    img3 = img3.astype(float) / 255.0

    # merge the enhanced and original with a bias
    # towards the original that expands over rounds
    bias = count // 4
    merged = ((2 + bias) * img + img3) / (3 + bias)

    # clip any values outside range
    merged = np.where(merged < 0.0, 0.0, merged)
    merged = np.where(merged > 1., 1., merged)

    return merged

print('Figure 5: Enhanced image edges')
show_transform(image_edges)

Figure 5: Enhanced image edges
  • Figure 5: The goal of image edge emphasis is to exaggerate key features in the image that might distinguish the object from the background. With this filter the amount of exaggeration decays over rounds because multiple rounds will start to degrade the image.

# flip a single image (3D)
def left_right_flip(img, count = 1):
    return np.fliplr(img)

# flip every image in 4D stack
def left_right_flip_all(x_train, y_train):
    x_train_flip = x_train.copy()
    for i in range(x_train.shape[0]):
        x_train_flip[i] = np.fliplr(x_train[i])
    
    x_train = np.concatenate((x_train, x_train_flip), axis=0)
    y_train = np.concatenate((y_train, y_train), axis=0)
    
    return (x_train, y_train)

print('Figure 6: Image mirroring')
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2, figsize = (4,10));
ax1.imshow(x_train[0]);
ax2.imshow(left_right_flip(x_train[0], 1));

Resizing the image¶
In [12]:
# image resize
# got some code from https://jdhao.github.io/2017/11/06/resize-image-to-square-with-padding/
def image_resize(img, count):
    # convert image to PIL format
    img = img * 255
    img = img.astype('uint8')
    pil_img = Image.fromarray(img)

    # choose a new size to resize to, less dramatic changes over rounds
    if count < 5:
        shrink = np.random.choice([38, 36, 28, 26, 24])
    elif 10 > count >= 5:
        shrink = np.random.choice([36, 34, 30, 28, 26])
    else:
        shrink = np.random.choice([34, 30, 28])
    
    # determine padding for smaller images, new size
    pad = max([(32 - shrink)//2, 0])
    new_size = (shrink, shrink)

    # resize using PIL anti-aliasing
    pil_img = pil_img.resize(new_size, Image.ANTIALIAS)

    # paste into center of new image
    new_im = Image.new("RGB", (32, 32))
    new_im.paste(pil_img, (pad, pad))

    # convert back to numpy
    img2 = np.array(new_im.getdata()).reshape(new_im.size[1], new_im.size[0], 3)

    img2 = np.where(img2 < 0, 0, img2)
    img2 = np.where(img2 > 255, 255, img2)

    # return image normalize to 0-1
    return  (img2.astype(float)) / (255.0)

print('Figure 7: Randomly resize the images')
show_transform(image_resize)

Figure 7: Randomly resize the images
  • Figure 7: Resizing the image should help the model generalize feature. The amount of resizing was constricted and biased towards size reduction due to the greater information loss from cropping. Translation was considered but rejected to reduce information loss and focus the model on the center of the image. This strategy is specific to CIFAR and should be reconsidered for other image sets.

Change the color tone of the image¶

In [13]:
# modified code from 
# https://www.semicolonworld.com/question/55219/changing-image-hue-with-python-pil
def shift_hue(arr, hout):
    rgb_to_hsv = np.vectorize(colorsys.rgb_to_hsv)
    hsv_to_rgb = np.vectorize(colorsys.hsv_to_rgb)
    r, g, b, a = np.rollaxis(arr, axis=-1)
    h, s, v = rgb_to_hsv(r, g, b)
    h = hout
    r, g, b = hsv_to_rgb(h, s, v)
    arr = np.dstack((r, g, b, a))
    return arr

def random_hue(img, count):
    """
    Colorize numpy image `original` with random
    `hue` (hue within 0-360); returns another numpy image.
    """
    # convert image to PIL
    img2 = img * 255
    img2 = img2.astype('uint8')
    pil_img = Image.fromarray(img2)

    # convert PIL image to RGBA, then to numpy
    rgba = pil_img.convert('RGBA')
    arr = np.array(np.asarray(rgba).astype('float'))
    
    # shift hue and convert back to PIL
    hue = np.random.choice(range(0, 360))
    new_im = Image.fromarray(shift_hue(arr, hue/360.).astype('uint8'), 'RGBA')
    new_im = new_im.convert('RGB')
    
    # convert back to numpy and normalize image  to 0-1
    img3 = np.array(new_im.getdata()).reshape(new_im.size[1], new_im.size[0], 3)
    img3 = (img3.astype(float)) / (255.0)
    
    # merge the enhanced and original with a bias
    # towards the original that expands over rounds
    bias = count // 4
    merged = ((1 + bias) * img + 1 * img3) / (2 + bias)

    # clip any values outside range
    merged = np.where(merged < 0.0, 0.0, merged)
    merged = np.where(merged > 1., 1., merged)

    return merged

print('Figure 8: Changing to color cast of the image')
show_transform(random_hue)

Figure 8: Changing to color cast of the image
  • Figure 8: Changes in color tone were achieved using small shifts in hue, merged back into the original image. The goal was to simulate different lighting situations while still producing realistic color palettes. ##### Augment random rows with random augmentations
  • This function with take a fraction of the data and 'mutate' it with one of the above transformations.
In [14]:
# start for loop with how many rounds to iterate over
def train_data_augment(x_train, y_train, fraction = 10, count =1):
    # get values for fraction the data for train and valid
    aug_count_t = len(x_train)//fraction

    # set up temp duplicate images
    x_train_aug = x_train.copy()
    y_train_aug = y_train.copy()

    # randomly select fraction of the images as a list of rows
    rows_t = np.random.choice(range(x_train.shape[0]), aug_count_t, replace = False)

    #loop over training data to augment
    for row in rows_t:
        n = np.random.rand()
        if n < 0.25:
            x_train_aug[row] = random_hue(x_train[row], count)
        elif n < 0.5:
            x_train_aug[row] = image_edges(x_train[row], count)
        elif n < 0.75:
            x_train_aug[row] = image_resize(x_train[row], count)
        else:
            x_train_aug[row] = rand_rotation_im(x_train[row], count)
    
        # assign correct target label
        y_train_aug[row] = y_train[row]

    return (x_train_aug, y_train_aug)

Model testing¶

  • Due to long training times only one model will be trained at a time. Models are selected by commenting and uncommenting lines 20-22. The boolean augment variable on line 5 determines whether the model is trained on augmented data or not. If augment is selected, one divided by FRACTION percent of the data is mutated each round. The EPOCHS determine how many epochs the model runs before starting a new round, tracked by the count variable. Each round loads the model from the last round with the best validation set accuracy. The batch size is increased every 5 rounds using the sequence in the batch_sizes list. The history of all the training is stored in a dictionary and then exported to a csv file.
In [15]:
# how many epoch of data fitting per round
EPOCHS = 1

# whether to train on augmented data or not
augment = True

# what fraction of the data to mutate with augmentation each round
FRACTION = 20

# every 5 rounds the batch size increases to generalize and fine tune
batch_sizes = [64, 128, 128, 256, 512, 512, 1028, 1028]

# collect the accuracy and loss for each round
history_dict = {}

# how many rounds (count) to train
for count in range(0,1):
    # choose a model to load
    if count == 0:
        current_model = alex_resnet_model() # Alexnet/ResNet hybrid
#         current_model = alex_resnet_dilation_only() # Alexnet/ResNet hybrid with dilation
#         current_model = alexnet_model() # model from class
        print(f'Training a {current_model.name} model ', end = '')
        if augment:
            print('with data augmentation.')
        else:
            print('without data augmentation.')
        
        # compile model with Adam solver
        current_model.compile(optimizer = 'adam', metrics=['acc'],
              loss=keras.losses.CategoricalCrossentropy(from_logits=True))
    
    # continue training a model from checkpoint
    else:
        current_model = tf.keras.models.load_model(f'{current_model.name}_{count - 1}.ckpt')
  
    # scale batch size to round
    batch_size = batch_sizes[min([count//5, len(batch_sizes)])]

    # augment the data if selected
    if augment:
        if count == 0:
            print('Mirroring all data. ', end = '')
            x_train, y_train = left_right_flip_all(x_train, y_train)
            print(f'New training data shape: {x_train.shape}')
        print(f'Augmenting {(1/FRACTION) * 100:.2f}% of the training data.', end = '')
        x_train, y_train = train_data_augment(x_train, y_train, fraction = FRACTION, count = count)
        print('Data augmentation complete')
  
    # filepath for checkpoints
    checkpoint_path = f'{current_model.name}_{count}.ckpt'

    # create a callback that saves the best model
    model_checkpoint_callback = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint(
            filepath=checkpoint_path, save_weights_only=False,
            monitor='val_acc', mode='max', save_best_only=True)
  
    # fit the model
    model_logs = current_model.fit(x_train, y_train,
                       epochs = EPOCHS,
                       batch_size = batch_size,
                       validation_data = (x_valid, y_valid),
                       callbacks = [model_checkpoint_callback],
                       verbose = 1)
  
    # save training information
    history_dict[count] = model_logs.history
    best = np.argmax(history_dict[count]["val_acc"])
    print(f'Round {count}:\tTraining {history_dict[count]["acc"][best]*100:.2f}', end = '\t')
    print(f'Validation {history_dict[count]["val_acc"][best]*100:.2f}\n')

# Save training information to a csv file
hist = []
for round_, score_logs in history_dict.items():
    for score_type, score_values in score_logs.items():
        for epoch, score in enumerate(score_values):
            hist.append({'model' : f'{current_model.name}', 'augmented' : f'{augment}', 
                'round' : round_, 'score_type' : score_type, 'epoch' : epoch, 'score' : score})
pd.DataFrame(hist).to_csv(f'{current_model.name}_aug_{augment}.csv', index = False)

Figure 8:
  • Figure 8: Compared with the baseline Alexnet model from class (blue), the model with residual connections (orange) learns much faster. It also plateaus at a higher level of training set accuracy (95.75% vs 92.86%) and validation set accuracy (79.12% vs 73.40%). The ResNet model is also 25% lighter (1,004,522 parameters vs 1,249,066). The use of data augmentation (green) resulted in a slight improvement in validation set accuracy, while compressing the training and validation accuracy gap. The continuous mutation of the training data resulted in a jagged training accuracy profile. The largest improvement from augmentation came early on in training, suggesting a slower rate of data augmentation should be explored. The use of dilation (red line) kept the training and validation accuracy very close, but both were at a lower level than the baseline model.
